embeds.title: From old money to Smart Money
embeds.description: For most people, seeing is believing: once they test out Eco and confirm that the benefits we’re offering are real, they become our champions and invite everyone they know to the app. But some people need to hear more first. If you’re reading this, odds are you’re one of these people.

messages.content: it's a lot... but it takes a lot to understand how broken the existing system is -- and how it can be fixed

The concept of abstracting the mechanics of crypto from the average user's experience is a good one, and obviously, tying Eco to real world vendors is necessary, but what about the online worlds? I've been a gamer since the late 70s, and the one thing no one is offering is a place, instead of a game. To make that happen, the first element really needs to be a currency and contract system that can tie the real world and the virtual world together. Ultimately, what many of us want to see is a 3D launcher that acts as our home base, but allows us to enter all the various virtual worlds out there, and when done, take us back into the launcher (what we call 'the hub') world to 'park'. Limited ability to transfer items from the online world to the hub world, where NFTs would confer value to them, even if the games they came from cease to exist, and something like Eco to buy and sell the NFTs.

oh  @mymiacca we just had an epic conversation in the waiting room on 'Smart Money'
Here's a teaser, but then I really do have to go

*A good product is simple. It should ‘just work’ For you.  
It only surprises you with what it can do, not by what it can’t.*

When we explain Eco to people for the first time, there's a clear moment when 'the lights go on' and they intuitively understand. Unsurprisingly, this is most often especially powerful when we're able to show, not tell them.But when they try to describe Eco to someone else, the best communicators are almost always left grasping for words. The only other time I’ve had the same feeling is when I drove a Tesla for the first time. After 90 seconds, I still could not figure out how to turn it on. I thought I was smart enough to know Elon wouldn’t design the cars to use physical keys for the ignition, but I couldn’t find the button that would turn on the car instead.. Since I was in a rush, I eventually swallowed my pride and googled it.
There is no button. DUH. You just press the break, shift into drive and go.

The common thread between myself and the aforementioned Eco users is that we both were ‘trained to look for a keyhole’ whether or not it made sense or not. The same can be said for the way most of us manage our day-to-day finances: why do we have checking accounts AND savings accounts? is there any difference besides the name (because they both pay nothing.)

Why do many of us spend with credit cards–a debt instrument? Doesn't this just set us up to make bad decisions, and make it harder to keep track of everything?  Why do we have an app for every little thing we do with our money? We can send emails instantly from anywhere we want to anywhere we want instantly for free. Why does it take 3-5 days to send money...even to yourself. Let alone internationally?
https://tenor.com/view/the-big-short-gif-15394428
Waiting for an Eco meme with this scene 😄

Let’s pause for a second. We have smart everything today: smart phones, smart houses, smart jewelry, even smart toothbrushes. We may not have flying cars (yet), but we do have smart ones that can already drive themselves well enough to give dumb money a whole new meaning. Before you even get in a Tesla, it winks its lights at you as if to say ‘I gotchu’ as it unlocks the door.  When you press the door handle, the door pops open as your music seamlessly transitions to the car system. The seat, and rest of car adjusts itself to your preferred settings, and then calculates how long it’ll take to get you to your desired destination, how much it’ll cost you, and suggests route changes to get whatever you need to get there.

*What does more enjoyable, riding in the Tesla, or wading through the ten different apps you use when trying to get your finances in order?*

A good product understands where you are and meets you there. A great product understands both where you are, and where you want to go–and then takes you there. Tesla’s Autopilot is the consummate ‘great product’ because when engaged, it smoothly takes control of the wheel, and handles everything so you don’t have to–so long as you keep an eye on the road! It does this until you decide you want to take back the reins, either for fun, or if something urgent or important comes up that you need to take the wheel for–which is actually all you need to do–then off you go! 

*Does this sound like your experience handling your money?*

Here're some quotes. 

`The reason that the Federal Reserve goes to such great lengths to make its organizational structure as confusing as possible is to cover up the massive conflicts of interest that are at the heart of that system. The fact is that the Federal Reserve System is comprised of a Board of Governors, 12 regional banks, and an Open Market Committee. The privately-owned member banks of each Federal Reserve Bank vote on the majority of the Reserve Bank’s directors, and the directors vote on members to serve on the Federal Open Market Committee, which determines monetary policy. What’s more, Wall Street is given a prime seat at the table, with tradition holding that the president of the powerful New York Federal Reserve Bank be given the vice chairmanship of the FOMC and be made a permanent committee member. In effect, the private banks are the key determinants in the composition of the FOMC, which regulates the entire economy.`

Also, the Feds decisions can't be overruled by anyone in the US.

You sound way more knowledgeable in this area than I do, but it seems to me that the rate of change to a different system will be as important as the dynamics of the new system itself. If a new system was to overtake the old very quickly, it concerns me that a collapse will occur that could harm everyone. Do you agree that the rate of change is important?

Yes, incredibly important... collapse in my mind is inevitable as some just won’t make the shift (they won’t be permitted to) that’s why I believe that tying labor and behaviors to the accumulation/depletion of points (let me call the “currency units” - CU’s going forward) would be very helpful for easing a path into use of the CU’s as a stand-alone medium of exchange.

What might be a possibility is that the accumulation of the CU occurs naturally by our process of life and then by virtue of smart governance a bit of it is accumulated as a reserve pool for those who are late to the party. They become eligible for something not unlike a universal basic income in the CU so that the rug isn’t pulled out from under them (this won’t be perfect mind you) but if we have EVERYONE on a common CU (that has decay properties so that it’s not unreasonably hoarded) then it would be reasonable to assume that we could do away with regressive tax policies and still have adequate funding for human needs. Remember in my thinking that the CU has these decay aspects that keeps it moving if you don’t want it to lose value.

Apologies as I’m very long winded and not a good teacher at all. Perhaps someone can do a better job of explaining the concept?

Wisdom of the collective crowd you know?

Ok, so points == currency units == CUs. And you see an element to DEvaluation? Wouldn't that imply there was an unlimited amount, which we are definitely not seeing here. Could you explain how the devaluation happens.

Devaluation in the same way as natural law. Hurricane, earthquake, volcano, tidal wave impact a human settlement.... what was there has been impacted and likely devalued. 1930’s dust bowl in the USA is another good example. Some places are naturally immune to some sorts of disasters and these fare better than others. If decay is programmed into the CU then there is an incentive to keep it circulating and in use as opposed to being hoarded. The problem with man made currencies weather backed by commodities or by force/coercion (overt or covert) is that they are subject to hoarding and creating scarcity. The CU I envision would defeat that algorithmically by have a programmed rate of decay that is dependent on behaviors of the CU holder(s) which would prevent it’s likelihood of being held too long or deployed in such a way as to be immune from devaluation. 

It’s no different than how the central banks around the world are playing the game now. The difference is that the bad actors / corrupt officials / military’s are able to pull the levers (or not) again my vision is that if you steal another human’s CU the algorithm will instantly devalue it and issue replacement CU to the victim of the thief... programmable CU is my thought. 

What are frequent flyer miles other than programmable CU with the airlines and banks determining the value? 

Mind you I’m not suggesting that one is stopped from accumulating, far from it, but hold your CU as capital for too long and it will experience decay... deploy it for beneficial uses and that might slow decay. All CU would experience decay but not by virtue of a central authority like an airline or bank or government but rather by the actions/inactions of its legitimate human owner.

The Saving Glut of the Rich | Ludwig Straub

Abstract:
There has been a large rise in savings by Americans in the top 1% of the income or wealth distribution over the past 35 years, which we call the saving glut of the rich. The saving glut of the rich has been almost as large as the global saving glut, and it has not been associated with an increase in investment. Instead, this rise in savings has been associated with substantial dissaving by the non-rich and dissaving by the government. A process by which the financial sector is unveiled reveals that rich households have accumulated substantial financial assets that are direct claims on household and government debt. Analysis using variation across states shows that the rise in top income shares has been important in generating the saving glut of the rich.

Last updated on 02/04/2021

https://scholar.harvard.edu/straub/publications/saving-glut-rich-and-rise-household-debt

Hoarding behavior?

@Exarare where do you think this behavior is coming from?

In a word… financial engineering, poor governance and uneven application of tax policy and administration that few among us have the capacity to understand. 

The world is awash in capital and unlike the industrial revolution, the information age combined with the US departure from the gold standard ushered in the ability to deploy fiat capital continuously. During the industrial revolution one had to allocate capital in a very intelligent and informed fashion. 

Today, so many more risks of the downside can be hedged and mitigated by competent "rules driven" financial engineering. If well executed, then ultimately, the only risk to capital is seizure (including theft) and/or forfeiture (with or without due process) across borders. Even these risks have been mitigated for the last five decades. Return on capital has become abstracted from its beneficiaries, it is only now with the advent of "social media" that awareness is raised about where capital is and what it is doing and even that is very opaque to the common individual.

Individuals can also only "consume" so much in a lifetime and dynastic (inherited) wealth has eluded nearly every family around the globe for the last five hundred years.
Most of it has been transferred to the state and or redistributed (revolution, estate taxes, corruption).

Rational behavior is difficult to find. A human's natural heuristic processing capacity is being impeded and slowed by a glut of information from our "always on" world that we just haven't evolved to process. It's becoming difficult for a human mind to see identifiable patterns, and so we act without seeing harmful second and third order consequences of our actions / inactions and this is to our collective detriment.

@Exarare In terms of a biological ecosystem acting as a model for a financial one, could an appreciating and/or depreciating CU be likened to photosynthesis? Injecting potential energy, (like ATP) into the system in predictable increments? 

What if a biological ecosystem was able to participate in a financial ecosystem as an independent actor. Imagine a wooded landscape, for example, was a distributed economic entity like the book store. Maybe it could afford to hire its own advocates, ecologists etc. An ongoing consensus about its health could be based on popular and expert human perception as well as distributed sensor data - this information could fulfill certain conditions that would trigger the ecosystem to take action on occasion - perhaps initiating its own tree-planting initiatives as an example. Meeting the systems ‘needs’ before the ‘wants'. So maybe a forest or lake could be its own decentralized steward of preservation and abundance. I don't see why it couldn't responsibly harvest its own resources helping the people who have a stake in it.  

I imagine the bulk of an ecosystem's wealth would be derived from the people's intent to depend on it throughout their lives. Maybe a special token is minted and transferred to the Amazon Jungle or Atmosphere for instance, each time a human is born. Maybe the appreciating stake generations of humans put into the ‘Atmosphere Entity’ could account for some of the appreciating CU which could bring financial energy to the system. 

How do we create value from a natural ecosystem by growing it, rather than selling it?

The title may be somewhat mis-leading but the content makes the principles pretty clear.

"In his book Sacred Economics, Charles Eisenstein states:  If the community is flourishing, then all within it will partake of the same abundance—or shortage—that nature provides.

The currency of exchange is gratitude and relationship rather than money. It includes a system of social and moral agreements for indirect reciprocity. So, the hunter who shared the feast with you could well anticipate that you would share from a full fishnet or offer your labor in repairing a boat.

The natural world itself is understood as a gift and not as private property, as such there are ethical constraints on the accumulation of abundance that is not yours. Well known examples of gift economies include potlatches or the Kula ring cycle, in which gifts circulate in the group, solidifying bonds of relationship and redistributing wealth.

The question of abundance highlights the striking difference between the market economies which have come to dominate the globe and the ancient gift economies which preceded them. There are many examples of functioning gift economies—most in small societies of close relations, where community well-being is recognized as the “unit” of success—where the interest of “we” exceeds that of “I.” In this time when the economies have grown so large and impersonal that they extinguish rather than nurture community well-being, perhaps we should consider other ways to organize the exchange of goods and services which constitute an economy."

messages.content: @Exarare isn't that kind of projecting that the natural world has what the author of those statements perceives as human values, as a way of further legitimizing those values?
Furthermore, it seems like the assumption that a gift economy is reciprocal is kind of removing the whole point of a gift economy as distinct from a non-gift economy.

Yes, the notion of reciprocity (a human observation) might be analogous to the natural law of conservation. Humans are merely manipulating (stewarding?) finite resources. I think the word gift isn’t so well suited to the idea. Give back or exchange might be better but the act of the reciprocity is a necessary act governed by natural law. Use it or loose it so to speak.

This gift economy concept seems naive to me. I do not necessarily like it, but I accept that Capitalism is being used as a metaphor for physical competition. Rather than compete purely militarily, I prefer we compete economically, constantly in a race to see who can get the most, the fastest. It beats killing each other. I also accept that selfishness is intrinsic to our species, and there is nothing wrong (or right) about it. How selfishness is HARNESSED is what makes a person 'good' or 'bad'. Capitalism embraces our selfishness, and harnesses it in a non-physical way. A gift economy seems to ignore our selfish nature, and that is why it seems naive to me.

Consider that the 10 commandments, for instance, are a set of rules that were established specifically because we do not naturally follow them. If everyone did not covet their neighbor's stuff, there would be no need for the commandment to tell us not to. Whatever system replaces Capitalism must be pragmatic about the human condition, and not try to fit us into a square hole of idealism that our roundness simply won't fit.

Yes I see your point @Subspace and understand that the “ideal” selfless model includes surrender of free will which any one who knows me will agree that I’m no fan of. I think that a competitive ECOsystem will enhance my ability to exercise that free will that I hold so dear. This is my main attraction to ECO, an ability to escape coercive behaviors imposed on my person and thus my labor and thus my capital. I want my say in how my labor is expended and so I don’t want to share an arbitrary portion with a system that adds no value.

Also, @JCoin, I'm curious to what extent you think you can predict what things are going to be meaningful (as per your definition) across cultures. Also, to what extent do you think that uniqueness and purposefulness trade off against each other?

Great question @Bryce  | Eco. I’ll have to think more on your question about the trade off. 

As for meaningful, I selected that as a criteria for a slightly different reason. 

In cultural experiences/exchanges in my past, I’ve been most drawn to acquiring/trading for things that i was able to perceive as meaningful (primarily through excitement about the item that the other person showed, photographs they share of them using it, etc.).

A good example from my own life was when I was in Vietnam. A man gave me a coin that he had flattened on a railroad, in exchange for a New York Yankees hat. The coin seemed so meaningful to him, that I was happy to exchange an item that was so meaningful to me (despite not needing the coin for any reason)!

I also found the coin to be unique (it was flattened in a way that couldn’t be repeated). 

It makes me think of whether it was purposeful, though. I don’t have much purpose for it, other than as a great story to tell.

Reading now, how are you relating the time variable?

Apollo's associate departures didn't seem to be about a lack of money. One former associate told Business Insider he'd reached the conclusion that the lifestyle was just too toxic: 

“I thought, 'I don't want to be spending my time doing this. I don't care how much you pay me.'" 

I’m just calling attention to the trade off of time/labor.

The folks referenced in the article are, in some cases, willing to forego their time for a greater monetary payout for that time (which again is a fixed constant) and the employer has introduced a speculative variable into the equation to act as a overtly coercive incentive... the term of retention. It’s a kind of put option with no equity. No different than hazard pay for front line workers 🧐

Now mind you there is nothing spectacular in the abilities of any of the first year folks who are toiling. They’ve made an assessment of the opportunity and some have decided that the trade off is ok with them but the “time component” was entirely manipulated by the contingency offered up by Apollo which was the term of the commitment.

I am a strong advocate for defending ones time, it is a uniform scarcity that can be deployed however one wishes and life experiences that are chosen rather than forced upon humans (by circumstance or otherwise) have by and large yielded better results for society. 

These folks have given up their time for a very specific and certain return. They’re not in control of the direction of their time.

At some point the diligence these folks perform will have been largely replaced by algorithms very accurately and intelligently deployed to prove or disprove the assumptions and “claims” of the bankers at firms like Apollo.

That these positions exist at all is due, in largest part, to legacy, non-uniform accounting processes and tax policies that differ across time and various jurisdictions. That and a target/victim’s inability to access and or redeploy capital efficiently or adequately hedge real world risks.
I mean, it seems like this is a political rebellion more than anything else.

You're right that the positions only exist because of incoherent external policies. This just seems like a case where the emotional toll of doing something that doesn't really matter for non-socially constructed reasons was able to get priced in. The fact that it also is resulting in the breakdown of a social contract is an unfortunate casualty,  but I can't view that as wholly negative, as that social contract is premised on the design of the system that they were working in making sense.

Financial engineering has begun to meet its match in an increasingly very connected world. Social contracts are being rewritten EVERYWHERE and I venture to say that projects like ECO are part of that rewrite. Capital needs to be deployed in order to maintain its value... I’ve long had a mantra “all value is embedded in time to completion” 

Ever wonder why accounting periods are structured the way they are? I mean in an always on world isn’t a reporting period arbitrary? So much change in motion now... a direct effect of the pandemic. It’s exposed so much BS in our highly securitized, risk hedged world and the gaping holes in our analysis of that world.

The crazy thing about the Apollo situation is that .07 percent of their total number of employees were able to make that much of an impact in terms of public/press awareness. That’s really pretty incredible... and all because of the focus on $ by so many.

messages.content: This was a great read!

I'm pretty sure philosophy only ever exists with self interest, which is sometimes greed. Being a philosopher is pretty self interested. You think you're right about something that people are wrong about, and you try to scale your beliefs by persuading people. That gets other people to do your work for you. Sometimes what they want doesn't look self interested (think Mozi or Singer, or for a more interesting example Diogenes) but their self still wants it, so it's disingenuous to not call it self interested even if their self-interest hopes to create a positive sum outcome.  

The issue isn't greed exactly, if greed is the desire for material objects, but directing selfish desire for a means, not an end. Money is a tool, albeit an abstract one, since money isn't really a material object. Tools are meant to be used to accomplish an objective. If the tool is using you, something is wrong. 

In the case of money, when it uses you, you just acquire it for no other purpose than to have it. That's not greed; if you hoard it you don't actually get anything real or valuable. If this project just leads to a bunch of people hoarding their gold like a bunch of maladjusted dragons, it's a failure. But, if the desire for wealth ends up driving people to be able to accomplish things that they'd otherwise fail at, it's a grand success.

I look at philosophy more as a way of interpreting the world, and a code to live by, vs a means of convincing others to change their point of view. But I do agree that selfishness is intrinsic to the human condition, and as such, is neither positive nor negative. Instead, how selfishness is harnessed is what determines it's positive or negative value. Which is why I ask the question of whether selfishness, in the form of greed, can coexist, in the same person, with a desire to change the world. I think it can, as long as the former desire is not naively assumed to not exist when the latter is being pursued. Boots on the ground, what I mean is that there are those in here who absolutely want to be part of the next 'thing' and through that, get rich, but as frosting on the cake, they also can have a clear conscience because in supporting this new paradigm, they are also moving us away from traditional monetary systems, and are thus making a positive difference for all humanity.

I do have one disagreement however, and that is when you said, 'if you hoard it you don't actually get anything real or valuable.' Hoarding money is done for many reasons, some of which is real, and does have value. An example is security from poverty, and freedom to live your life as you choose.

I think the trend of why resources are not controlled and managed by those who use them is a consequence of scale. Sure, when the mayordomo is herself a farmer who also uses the canals, she acts as a representative of the other farmers, and is acting in all of their interests. But when that canal is connected to a larger series of canals, and eventually to rivers that have dams, then ultimately and intrinsically, the distance of the ones who manage the highest scale resources are no longer those that actually use them.

I think this can be said of money as well. Those at the highest levels of control are themselves so wealthy, that the way they view and use money is in no way similar to how the average person does. As such, while they know that money has to go to the bottom-most level to keep the whole system running, the vested interest in making the lowest levels able to grow to the highest doesn't exist. Quite the opposite, if that was facilitated in any way, those at the top would suddenly lose power and control, and so their interest is to actually keep things as they are or make it even harder for those at the bottom.
Their only fear, I imagine, is the boundary between making things harder, and having the populace forcibly remove them.

And they mitigate this by allowing a very few people to trickle up, which 'proves' that it is possible, and convinces the populace that if they just work hard enough, or just get lucky enough, that they too can achieve wealth. And if they do NOT achieve wealth, it is their own fault.

Dispatch 2: A myriad of factors. One would be the culture of the population involved.

i.e., Governance. In cultures that appreciate appreciate technical excellence, you have more political leaders with science and/or engineering backgrounds. In another where pride and power is important, people who are able to make the electorate feel good about themselves get voted. While some, where the whole existence of a country depended on efficient management of limited local resources and regional/international political goodwill, leaders with strong administrative capabilities stood out.

But sometimes, it's also a matter or scale and luck.

Let's say, we have a culture which appreciates technical excellence, and this culture was able to prosper and grow to a size that gives it the scale, power, affluence and influence across large parts of the world. That would influence how other cultures adjust themselves to work with this culture on their terms.

But, say, we have the culture of pride and power, with the scale, power, affluence and influence that affects much of the other cultures it interacts with, then there would be more decision makers who'd be affecting change and progress that seeks to appeal to pride and power, as opposed to technical excellence or administrative efficiency.

Well. If there was a powerful culture that had its roots dug deep into respect for nature, we'd probably not have as much issues as we have now, when it comes to our current eco-system, and the maintenance of it.

An oversimplification, but as of now, probably the best I can come up with in words, as least in regards to this 1 small little aspect.

Re Dispatch 2: my perspective is that there’s 2 major factors in driving collaboration/collusion in systems: social and economic. The social factor includes how others may judge one based on their decisions which affect ones future prospects (you could argue that this is also economic, but I think that’s a secondary effect). The economic factor is simply the material benefits one earns.

The acequia community may be either close knit (ie everyone knew each other, got along well) and/or all farmers had an optimally shared incentive to keep the system running (ie there’s no way for one to not keep the system running without losing economic resource. On other words their have a Nash equilibrium)

At the most general level, I think this isn’t present on our society because 1) there’s a level of anonymity, or diffusion of responsibility in large populations and 2) resources are siloed at many levels such as geographical, political, temporal. Someone/group always can extract more  economic incentives for their particular ‘silo’ without any huge repercussions on social factors to detract them from doing what they do.

Blockchain technology fits in here as something that could potentially remove such divisions (silos) by making resources more accessible to people, and making exploitation economically undesirable. The social factor seems trickier, as it could apply to governance of blockchains and de-anonymization of chains. I personally prefer a fully anonymous chain, as it doesn’t predispose new systems to our old social biases. Although I also think the other side of this is that we get a lot of greed in crypto markets that may not work to benefit everyone.
Does the anonymity that you're talking about produce benefits that you can identify?
How do "silos" at different levels interact?
!grant @David_1391 30 points.

Definitely. In a way, that was a simplified 'part 1' of my thought about the whole thing.

A culture can start off in one way, and have their priorities changed as they grow, affecting their choice of governance.

Like in my country, there's a constant debate about its leadership. Someone put it succinctly (I can't remember where I read it from but I wished I had also thought of it this way sooner lol) , that the biggest criticism boils down to how the local government went from having good leaders with ideas and foresight in its make-up, to having good administrators instead.

It sort of makes sense if you understand our history. We were a tiny nation with no natural resources surrounded by larger neighbors that were not necessarily friendly, primarily because of our racial makeup. We needed leaders who could push past these hurdles and lead us forward.

Now, however, we're a relatively stable country. We went from trying to survive, to trying to make everyone happy.

It's kinda relevant to the dispatch because we find ourselves having people in charge who did not have the 'proper' qualifications controlling important parts of the govt.

So, apart from culture being the foundation for how a society chooses its leaders, you'll also nepotism. This will also include political nepotism, in that people are chosen (and sold to the public to be chosen) to consolidate power for those in power.

So I guess some of the major factors boils down to the 
- The cultural foundations of a society
- The current goals of the society (survival, to thrive, etc)
- The goals of the people in power

The combination of these 3 would determine the chances of suitable/unsuitable candidates being chosen for the right/wrong roles managing the right/wrong resources

About your question on anonymity: 
definitely, I think anonymity is needed to maintain permission-less property of systems. It also strips away lot of biases (eg. gender, appearance, ethnicity, socioeconomic status ...) that we are plagued with in current systems.

Interaction between ‘silos’: not sure if I have a good answer. But here are my thoughts.
I’d like to first define a silo as a group of people who can extract extra economic value via collusion (ie aligned economic incentives). They would be colluding to extract more of a scarce resource that the wouldn’t be able to individually. In that sense, their interactions would be dictated by what resource they are extracting, and what other groups (‘silos’) are targeting the same resources for different purposes. In this sense their interactions would probably adversarial across all levels.

messages.content: Re: Dispatch 2: In my experience working in the healthcare industry not even death of fellow people will demotivate the greed of the wealthiest to continue hoarding more. Amazon grew its profits over the last year by insane amounts and was able to bribe more government officials into cutting their federal taxes. Perhaps this is a fundamental problem of greed that is hard coded into the DNA of many people, where the more money and power they accumulate, the worse their problem becomes and the more detached they become from humanity.

I think your healthcare example is a great illustration that economic incentives drive decision making in a capitalistic world, regardless of morals. Regulation may help but it’s a form of centralization that makes the system vulnerable to exploit. 
I think that’s also why it great that Eco team is partly vested in Eco points. It aligns incentives for everyone to prevent selfish behavior.
